      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA procedures and version control; solver release notes reviewed.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 used under institutional QA protocol. Release validation suite confirms solver correctness for viscous incompressible flows. Version and license documented in simulation log."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes manufacturer-supplied benchmark suite for rotating machinery and viscous flow; no known defects relevant to pump hemolysis simulation.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent benchmark suite for rotating reference frame and species transport reviewed. No open defect reports affecting hemolysis scalar transport identified in release notes."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index for NIH quantity of interest less than 5% on the production mesh.",
      "rationale": "Three-mesh Richardson extrapolation yields GCI = 3.2% on the 5.8 M element production mesh. Spatial order of convergence p = 1.94, consistent with second-order discretization. Temporal convergence confirmed with 5-degree impeller rotation time-step."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "In-vitro test conditions (fluid properties, temperature, hematocrit) documented and within ±10% of COU operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments performed with bovine blood at 37°C, hematocrit 33±2%. COU specifies human blood at 37°C, hematocrit 30–35%. Fluid viscosity and density within 8% of COU values. Test boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, outlet pressure) match CFD boundary conditions within measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Relative error between predicted and measured NIH less than 15% at the validation operating point; comparison metric documented.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH = 0.0041 g/100 L; measured NIH = 0.0044 ± 0.0006 g/100 L at 3.5 L/min, 3000 RPM. Relative error 6.8%, well within 15% criterion. Uncertainty in experimental measurement (±14%) exceeds model error, indicating model is not the dominant source of uncertainty at this operating point."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model QOI (NIH, relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to the clinical acceptance criterion RH < 1.",
      "rationale": "The primary QOI is the normalized index of hemolysis, which is directly converted to the relative hemolysis index RH by normalization against the predicate device NIH. The acceptance criterion RH < 1 is the regulatory threshold for Class II CPB devices. QOI relevance is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on the same pump geometry and at operating conditions overlapping the COU envelope; at least one flow-speed combination within COU range validated.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, identical to the COU device. One of the five COU flow-speed combinations (3.5 L/min, 3000 RPM) is directly validated. The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is applied under the theoretical precondition that the stress–exposure relationship is linear and time-independent; this precondition is satisfied at the validated mid-range point. The remaining four COU operating points, including the high-shear condition at 2 L/min, 4500 RPM, extend into a stress regime where the linearity precondition has not been independently verified for this device geometry."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence of residuals to at least 1e-5 for continuity and momentum; hemolysis scalar residual to 1e-6.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to continuity residual < 8e-6 and momentum residuals < 2e-6. Hemolysis scalar transport residual < 5e-7. Mass imbalance < 0.01%. Convergence confirmed by monitoring NIH over last 200 iterations with variation < 0.3%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary conditions and material properties verified against test documentation.",
      "rationale": "Independent review of simulation setup files performed by senior analyst not involved in model construction. Boundary conditions, material properties, and hemolysis model coefficients verified against published FDA benchmark documentation and test reports. No discrepancies found."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Hemolysis model form (power-law stress–exposure) documented with literature justification; turbulence model selection justified for pump flow regime.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law model (dH/dt = C * tau^alpha * t^beta) is selected based on its established use in FDA benchmark studies. The SST k-omega turbulence model is selected for its documented performance in rotating machinery with adverse pressure gradients. The power-law formulation carries the theoretical precondition that hemolysis accumulation is linear in the exposure scalar across the shear-stress range of the COU; this is explicitly noted as an underlying assumption of the model form. Validation at the mid-range point supports model adequacy there, and the acceptance criteria for this factor do not include a check that the linearity precondition holds across the full five-point COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity analysis performed for key model inputs (viscosity, hematocrit, power-law coefficients C, alpha, beta); dominant inputs identified.",
      "rationale": "One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis performed for blood viscosity (±15%), hematocrit (±10%), and Giersiepen–Wurzinger coefficients. NIH is most sensitive to the exponent alpha (±12% NIH per ±5% alpha). Nominal coefficient values from Giersiepen et al. (1990) used throughout. Parametric uncertainty in coefficients is the dominant model input uncertainty source."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least three independent experimental replicates at the validation operating point; sample-to-sample variability reported.",
      "rationale": "Five independent in-vitro hemolysis measurements performed at 3.5 L/min, 3000 RPM using fresh bovine blood from separate donors. Coefficient of variation across replicates 8.3%, within acceptable biological variability for hemolysis testing. Mean and standard deviation reported."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; equivalency of input parameters between validation and COU conditions is addressed under Test Conditions factor.",
      "rationale": "At Model Risk Level 2, formal equivalency mapping of all input parameters between the validation scenario and the full COU envelope is not required. The Test Conditions factor addresses the primary fluid property equivalency. This factor is scoped to not-assessed consistent with MRL 2 requirements."
    }
  ],
